{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/the-trouble-with-predictions-66e215c995bc", "time": 1683005212.762534, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/the-trouble-with-predictions-66e215c995bc/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "The Trouble with Predictions. All models are wrong, but some are\u2026 | by Pavan B Govindaraju | Towards Data Science", "h1": "The Trouble with Predictions", "description": "Predictions from various epidemic models are driving crucial global policies. But their estimates are all over the place \u2014 So which one do we trust? To predict, we create an approximate version of\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/mathematics-life-and-death-how-disease-models-shape-national-shutdowns-and-other", "anchor_text": "all over the place", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/23-01-2020-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)", "anchor_text": "WHO", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncertainty_quantification#Forward_uncertainty_propagation", "anchor_text": "uncertainty quantification", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/There_are_known_knowns", "anchor_text": "unknown unknowns", "paragraph_index": 12}], "all_paragraphs": ["All models are wrong, but some are useful", "Predictions from various epidemic models are driving crucial global policies. But their estimates are all over the place \u2014 So which one do we trust?", "For this, we need to understand the various sources that cause the difference or error.", "To predict, we create an approximate version of the problem \u2014 the model, and with it comes the modeling error. For example, we often use a constant speed to estimate travel time.", "Models depend on parameters and these are reported as a range, in contrast to an exact number. The reproductive number (R0) for COVID-19 is an example and ranges from 1.4\u20132.5 as per the initial WHO estimate.", "Now, depending on how non-linear your model is, even small differences in these parameters can cause large changes in the outcome of interest. This range in the output can be propagated using uncertainty quantification for certain problems.", "Our models could be based on equations (deterministic) or using data (statistical). Calculating the output given the input parameters involves certain approximations.", "For example, in deterministic approaches, if we are to model things as a function of time using equations, we break down the problem into intervals and obtain solutions for each of them.", "In a statistical approach, for example, using a neural network, we are creating an approximation for the original function to be evaluated.", "Sometimes, the calculation itself can be approximated, say, by reducing the number of dependent variables and solving a smaller system for the output.", "All the above three sources of error are accrued during the calculation of output and are termed as numerical error. Note that this can be estimated only under strict assumptions on the function and algorithm used to evaluate.", "Thus, errors can occur from several sources and can be quantified, at best, only for some of the steps involved. However, most modeling efforts operate under the maxim of \u201csomething better than nothing\u201d.", "\u201cunknown unknowns\u201d \u2014 Once the dependent variables have been listed, there is always the possibility of new variables that have not been considered or even defined, yet are critical to the outcome.", "When all models are \u201cwrong\u201d and some are useful, how do we ascertain which model to use?", "Companies are driven by monetary incentives and have well-defined notions of \u201cuseful\u201d. Models that are maximizing a utility metric (money) over time are chosen.", "In research settings, where \u201cuseful\u201d does not have a clear-cut definition, how does one approach gain merit over the other? Citations, funding, muscle?", "The holy grail of modeling should be \u201crobust + accurate\u201d models \u2014 those that are not very sensitive to parameters and underlying methods.", "Several implementations of it can differ on underlying details, but the model will gain favor due to reproducibility, consistency and most of all, reliability as accuracy is also guaranteed on repetition.", "In summary, forecasting should prefer models with little to no tunable parameters and match validation with measurements for a wide range of inputs.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Specializes in not specializing || Blogging about data, systems and tech in general"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F66e215c995bc&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fthe-trouble-with-predictions-66e215c995bc&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fthe-trouble-with-predictions-66e215c995bc&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------